    <p class="sl">Why Melbourne chimneys need regular attention</p>
    <h2>Melbourne&rsquo;s Housing Stock &mdash; And Why Chimney Maintenance Matters Here</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Melbourne has one of the most varied housing stocks of any Australian city. The inner and middle suburbs are defined by Victorian, Edwardian and interwar period homes &mdash; many featuring original brick chimneys and fireplaces that were designed as the primary heat source and are now used recreationally. These older systems require careful attention: lime mortar deteriorates over time, heritage flue liners crack with thermal cycling, and narrow Victorian flue dimensions accumulate creosote faster than modern systems. The middle and outer suburbs contain a large stock of 1950s through 1990s homes, many fitted with slow combustion wood heaters that are the primary or backup heat source during Melbourne&rsquo;s cold winters. Melbourne&rsquo;s climate &mdash; cold, damp winters from May through August with regular overnight lows under 5&deg;C &mdash; means wood heaters and fireplaces work hard every season. Heavy winter use accelerates creosote buildup. The Dandenong Ranges, Yarra Valley, Mornington Peninsula and outer north-west experience particularly cold winters, with residents using wood heating more intensively than in inner Melbourne. Regular professional cleaning keeps these systems safe, efficient and compliant with home insurance requirements.</p></div>
  </section>

